# MeshCore Hashtag Channel System (Firmware v1.11.0+): Architecture & Implementation

## 1. Channel Name Parsing & Storage in Firmware

**Channel Record Structure:** MeshCore stores channels in a fixed-size table (up to **40 channels per node**). Each channel occupies a 68-byte record in the devices flash file `/channels2`. The record layout is identical for all channels (public, private, or hashtag): [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/meshcore-dev/MeshCore/8.4-contact-and-channel-storage)

*   **Offset 03:** *Unused/Reserved* (for future use) [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/meshcore-dev/MeshCore/8.4-contact-and-channel-storage)
*   **Offset 435:** **`name`** (32 bytes, null-padded UTF-8)  the channels display name. This field **includes the leading # character** if present. For example, a channel named #emergency is stored literally as `'#','e','m','e','r','g','e','n','c','y',0,0,...` (padded to 32 bytes). There is no separate flag or field to mark a channel as a hashtag channel  the `'#'` in the name is the indicator. [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/meshcore-dev/MeshCore/8.4-contact-and-channel-storage)
*   **Offset 3667:** **`secret`** (32 bytes)  the channels 256-bit encryption key (binary). If the channel uses a pre-shared key (PSK), this is the Base64-decoded key. In the case of hashtag channels, this secret is automatically calculated from the name (explained below). [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/meshcore-dev/MeshCore/8.4-contact-and-channel-storage)

<small>*Source: MeshCore ChannelDetails structure*</small> [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/meshcore-dev/MeshCore/8.4-contact-and-channel-storage)

Each channel record is identified by its **index (039)** which corresponds to its slot in this table. **Index 0** is typically the default Public channel (preconfigured), and one slot may be used for the special admin channel if configured (for remote admin commands). The remaining slots can be used for any combination of user-defined private channels or hashtag channels. [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/meshcore-dev/MeshCore/8.4-contact-and-channel-storage)

**Handling of # Prefix:** In firmware v1.11.0 and later, the presence of `'#'` as the first character of the channel name triggers special handling for the key: the firmware (or companion app) will **auto-generate the `secret`** for that channel name instead of expecting the user to supply one. Specifically, the convention is:

*   The 32-byte secret key for a `#`-prefixed channel is derived **deterministically from the channel name**. In practice, MeshCore uses the channel names hash as the key. The common approach observed is to take the **SHA-256 of the full name string (including #) and use the first 16 bytes of that hash as the 128-bit key.** For example, the channel #test produces a secret key `9cd8fcf22a47333b591d96a2b848b73f` (128-bit hex), which is exactly the first half of SHA-256("#test"). Likewise, #switzerland yields `8ad1ce57ad257627090ed28413c1f0b7` as the key  matching the hash of its name. This scheme means **any node can independently compute the key from the known channel name**, enabling easy federation of open channels. [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/), [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/) [\[jkingsman.github.io\]](https://jkingsman.github.io/meshcore-packet-knife/) [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/)

*   The `calcHash()` function referenced in the MeshCore code likely implements this derivation when saving/loading channels. Thus, when you **create or join a hashtag channel**, you only specify the name (with `#`), and the system sets the 32-byte secret automatically. In the channels table on disk, the derived key is stored in the `secret` field just like a normal PSK. [\[pugetmesh.org\]](https://pugetmesh.org/meshcore/)

**Storage Example:** The default **Public** channel (index 0) is stored with name `"Public"` and a known PSK. By default, MeshCore preloads Public with the well-known key (e.g. Base64 `"izOH6cXN6mrJ5e26oRXNcg=="` which decodes to hex `8b3387e9c5cdea6ac9e5edbaa115cd72`). A hashtag channel, say #weather, if added at index 1, would be stored with `name="#weather"` and `secret` = first 16 bytes of SHA-256("#weather"). The `'#'` is stored in the name field and is the only indicator that the channel is publicly derivable. [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/meshcore-dev/MeshCore/8.4-contact-and-channel-storage)

**Index Assignment:** Hashtag channels do **not use a special index range**; they occupy the next available slot like any other channel. There is no rigid mapping of particular index numbers to hashtag channels  its up to how the user organizes channels on their node. For instance, one node might have `#emergency` in slot 1 and `#news` in slot 2, while another node might have those same channels in slots 3 and 4. This difference in index doesnt prevent communication (see Protocol section below on how nodes reconcile channel identity). The only semi-fixed slots are index 0 (often Public) and possibly the highest slot for the Admin channel, but hashtag channels are otherwise dynamic. In summary, the `#` channels are **not segregated in storage**; theyre simply channels with a name that follows a special pattern and a predictable key.

**Capacity Consideration:** Each node can hold up to 40 channels total (including all types). Thus, using many hashtag channels consumes those slots just like private channels would. Unused slots are simply empty (and not written to disk to save space). The channel name length limit is 31 characters (plus null terminator), which is plenty for typical short hashtags. [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/meshcore-dev/MeshCore/8.4-contact-and-channel-storage)

## 2. Discovery & Joining Mechanics for Hashtag Channels

Hashtag channels are designed for **ad-hoc group communication**  you can join one if you know its name, without needing an explicit invite or pre-shared secret exchange. However, **MeshCore does not advertise available channels over the air in a user-friendly way**; discovery is mostly out-of-band or community-driven:

*   **Manual Joining:** To join a hashtag channel, a user (via the MeshCore app or CLI) must add a new channel with the `#` name. In the companion app, they would type the channel name (including `#`). On firmware v1.11+, thats all  the device will derive the key and start listening on that channel. On older firmware, the app would also need to provide the PSK explicitly (the app could compute it, or the user might paste it from a community list). In either case, once the channel is added to your devices channel list, your node will **listen for traffic on that channels frequency/settings** and attempt to decrypt messages with the derived key.

*   **Open by Default or Require Configuration:** **Nodes do not automatically join all hashtag channels by default**  you have to configure each channel you care about. For example, a brand-new node knows only the default Public channel; it wont suddenly join #emergency unless you add that channel to it. The openness of `#` channels refers to *accessibility*, not that they are auto-joined. Thus, joining is an explicit action but doesnt require obtaining a secret from someone  the name is the key.

*   **Network-Wide Flooding:** When a node sends a message to a channel (hashtag or not), it will be received by any node within range that is *configured for the same channel*. MeshCore uses **flood routing** for group channels: messages are broadcast and repeated by any repeaters, reaching all subscribers in the mesh. Theres no need to formally join a channel in the sense of registration; adding it to your channel list is sufficient to start receiving. Because flooding is used, you do not need to discover individual peers  if your radio is listening on the channel freq and has the right key, youll hear any traffic on it. [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/)

*   **Distinguishing Hashtag Channels in Discovery:** In periodic node advertisements (used for sharing presence and identity), MeshCore does not broadcast channel names (to avoid clutter and potential info leak). So your node doesnt explicitly tell others I have #weather channel. Instead, discovery of channels is primarily via human coordination:
    *   *Community Lists:* Communities publish lists of popular `#` channels on forums or websites (like use **#emergency** for emergencies, **#local** for neighborhood chat, etc.). New users learn about these and add them.
    *   *QR Codes:* MeshCore supports sharing channels via QR codes (containing name and key). Scanning a QR for a hashtag channel is easy since the key can be encoded or re-derived. Many communities provide QR codes for their open channels to simplify joining.
    *   *Trial and Convention:* Because the key space is derived from names, one could theoretically attempt to discover channels by guessing names. Tools exist (e.g., *MeshCore Packet Knife*) that can attempt to identify a channel name by brute-forcing known hashes from intercepted packets. However, in practice this is not how users join; its more of a proof-of-concept. Instead, common hashtag channels are known by convention or announced publicly. [\[jkingsman.github.io\]](https://jkingsman.github.io/meshcore-packet-knife/), [\[jkingsman.github.io\]](https://jkingsman.github.io/meshcore-packet-knife/)

*   **Open Channel Mechanism vs Private:** Unlike a private channel (where nodes must exchange an exact 256-bit key ahead of time), a hashtag channels *credentials* are entirely contained in its name. Think of the `#name` as a **well-known group identifier.** Anyone who independently configures the same identifier will share the traffic. Theres no handshake or central server to join; its just tuning into the right party line.

*   **Are They Open to Join by Default?** *Yes*, in the sense that having the name is enough to join, *no* in the sense that a node wont join unless instructed. They **do not require any permission**  knowing the name *is* the permission. All hashtag channels are effectively open/public channels, so if two strangers set up devices and both add #weather, theyll end up on the same channel and hear each other (assuming they are in RF range).

*   **Firmware Distinction During Join:** The firmware doesnt need a special procedure to log into an open channel. When you issue a `CMD_SET_CHANNEL` for a `#` channel (with no explicit key provided), firmware v1.11 will recognize the `#` and generate the key, then simply add it to the channel list. It doesnt treat it differently thereafter  from this point on, its just another channel in the table that it will include in its receive loop and use for send if addressed. Older firmware (pre-1.11) isnt aware of this convention, so the companion app must supply a key. In other words:
    *   **New firmware**: You can join by just name; device does `if (name[0]=='#') key = hash(name)`.
    *   **Old firmware**: It expects both name and key. If you only give name, it wont derive anything (and youd have an unencrypted channel which MeshCore doesnt allow, or just an inert entry). Therefore, older apps would fill in the key field by computing the hash on the host side and sending it down (so the behavior *appears* seamless to the user if the app is updated).

*   **Channel Advertisements:** MeshCores protocol does send out small advertisements (adverts) with identity info (for routing and contact), but these contain things like node ID, maybe primary channel, etc., not a list of all group channels. So, your node doesnt automatically learn that someone nearby is using #rescue, maybe I should join. Theres currently no mesh-protocol message that says *invite to channel* (though a user could manually share a channel via contact exchange or by sending the name in a message). The emphasis is that hashtag channels are a **user-coordinated joining** process, often guided by community knowledge or emergency guidelines.

*   **Leaving a Channel:** Since theyre open, leaving is simply removing it from your devices list if you no longer want to monitor it. Theres no network action required. In effect, each node independently decides which open channels to subscribe to.

**Summary:** Discovery of `#` channels is mostly **social** (via documentation or word of mouth) rather than automatic radio discovery. Once known, joining is as easy as adding the channel name in your device. All nodes that have done so will communicate as a group. The `#` prefix idea ensures that *any number of nodes can converge on the same key without coordination*  a powerful concept for building impromptu networks (for example, at an event everyone might agree use #eventchat). As the Swiss MeshCore group notes, channels starting with `#` are not encrypted, everybody can read along  so they intentionally publicize those channel names for everyone to join. [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/)

## 3. Protocol-Level Implementation Details

At the protocol level, **hashtag channels use the same mechanisms as any other channel**  the differences lie in how the key is obtained, not in how messages are sent. MeshCores companion radio protocol defines a set of commands for managing channels and sending messages. Key relevant commands include:

*   **`CMD_GET_CHANNEL` (0x1F / 31)**  Retrieve channel details for a given index. The request payload is a single byte (the channel index). The firmware responds with the channels info (likely a structured payload containing the name and some form of the key or a status code if not set). This is used by companion apps to enumerate channels on the device. For instance, after connecting, an app might call `CMD_GET_CHANNEL` for indices 0,1,2,... until it hits empty slots to get the list of configured channels and their names. [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/ripplebiz/MeshCore/6.1-companion-radio-protocol)

*   **`CMD_SET_CHANNEL` (0x20 / 32)**  Define or update a channel at a given index. This command is how a new channel (including hashtag channels) is added. The payload structure is: `[channel_index (1 byte), name (32 bytes), psk_base64 (...)]`. The name is a fixed 32-byte field (null-terminated if shorter). After the name string, a Base64-encoded PSK may follow in the payload. For **private channels**, the app will send the actual key (as Base64 text) in this field. For **hashtag channels** on new firmware, the app can send an empty string or omit the PSK  the firmware will notice the `#` in the name and generate the key internally. On older firmware, the app would include the Base64 of the hash-derived key to accomplish the same result (because that firmware wouldnt generate it itself). In either case, after `CMD_SET_CHANNEL`, the device will store the channel name and key in its `/channels2` store and begin using it. **Note:** When setting a channel that already exists, this command updates it (e.g. renaming or changing key). Typically hashtag channels dont need changing  theyre either present or not. [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/ripplebiz/MeshCore/6.1-companion-radio-protocol)

*   **`CMD_SEND_CHANNEL_TXT_MSG` (0x03)**  Send a text message to a group channel. The payload for this command is: `[txt_type (1 byte), channel_index (1 byte), timestamp (4 bytes), text (UTF-8...)]`. Here `channel_index` tells the firmware which channels encryption to use (which determines frequency and PSK). The firmware will package the text into an encrypted mesh packet and broadcast it. This command is used for all group messages; it does not know or care if the channel is hashtag or not. The **txt\_type** field can indicate plain text vs CLI command, but for normal user messages its 0 (`TXT_TYPE_PLAIN`). [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/ripplebiz/MeshCore/6.1-companion-radio-protocol)

*   **Reception Path:** When a mesh packet is received, the firmware must determine which channel it belongs to in order to decrypt it. MeshCore likely includes a small header or uses the packets metadata to identify the channel. Typically, this could be done by including an 8-bit channel ID in the message. In MeshCore, a simpler method is often used: try the packets **MAC (message authentication code)** or attempt decryption with each known channel key. Because the channel count is small (<=40), a device can iterate through its channel list and check which key successfully decrypts the packet. However, there are hints MeshCore might tag packets with a short identifier:
    *   The `calcHash()` 4-byte value in the channel record might be a channel identifier broadcast in clear to hint the channel (like Meshtastic uses a channelIndex field in messages). If so, a node could match that to pick the right key without brute-forcing all. But regardless of method, this is internal  for the SDK or external observer, you simply get messages on channels youve configured.

*   **Response Codes & Behavior:** These channel operations result in standard response codes. For example, after `CMD_SET_CHANNEL`, the device may return a generic success code. There isnt a special RESP\_CHANNEL\_ADDED  the confirmation is implicit. If something goes wrong (e.g. channel table full), an error code is returned. The protocol doesnt differentiate failed because key not provided vs other errors on older firmware; it would likely just NACK if you tried to add a channel without a key on a version that requires one.

*   **Encryption & Transmission:** MeshCore uses AES-256-CTR encryption for all channel messages. When sending on a channel, the node looks up the 32-byte secret for that channel and encrypts the payload. Hashtag channels are no exception  they are encrypted in transit. The only difference is the key is well-known (derived from name). So over-the-air, a hashtag channel message is encrypted data; a third-party cant read it unless they also know the channel name. There is no plaintext broadcast mode (except perhaps beacons or very low-level adverts). Thus, protocol frames for channel messages always carry ciphertext plus maybe some metadata. [\[localmesh.nl\]](https://www.localmesh.nl/en/meshcore-encryption-details/), [\[localmesh.nl\]](https://www.localmesh.nl/en/meshcore-encryption-details/)

*   **Identifying Hashtag vs Private in Protocol:** There is no explicit flag this is a hashtag channel in the protocol. When an app calls `CMD_GET_CHANNEL`, the returned name might include `#`, which is how the app can identify it as an open channel. For instance, if `CMD_GET_CHANNEL(2)` returns name #bot (and possibly the PSK or a hash of it), the companion app could infer that key = hash(name) (especially if the device is new enough to have done that). In practice, the device might not send the actual key over the companion link for security; it may send just the name and perhaps an indicator if the channel is default. The companion *could* recalc the key if needed (though usually it wouldnt need to  it can trust the device has it).

**Name-to-Index Mapping:** On the device, channels are referenced by their index in commands like `CMD_SEND_CHANNEL_TXT_MSG`. High-level applications (like an SDK) often abstract this by letting you send by name. Under the hood, the SDK would translate the name #emergency to the appropriate index. It might do so by caching the result of `CMD_GET_CHANNEL` calls, or by searching when needed:

*   If the channel name is found in the cached list, use its index.
*   If not found and the name starts with `#`, a smart SDK might decide to add the channel on the fly (since it knows it can derive the key). This is a design choice  see SDK Integration below.

**Protocol Example (Adding and Using a Hashtag Channel):**

Suppose we want to use `#emergency` on a device running v1.11:

1.  **Add Channel:** The companion sends `CMD_SET_CHANNEL` with index = next free (say 1), name = #emergency, and leaves PSK blank. Firmware sees `#` and generates key = `e1ad578d25108e344808f30dfdaaf926` (which is the known hash for "#emergency"). It stores the channel and returns success. [\[pugetmesh.org\]](https://pugetmesh.org/meshcore/), [\[pugetmesh.org\]](https://pugetmesh.org/meshcore/)
2.  **Send Message:** The app calls `CMD_SEND_CHANNEL_TXT_MSG` with channel\_index = 1 and the text. The firmware packages it, uses the key just generated, encrypts Help needed! and broadcasts. All nodes in range that also have #emergency configured will attempt decryption  those that derive the same key succeed and pass the message up.
3.  **Receive Message (other side):** A node that has `#emergency` in its channel list (with the same derived key) gets the radio packet. Suppose the protocol includes an 8-bit channel ID in the packet header. The node matches it to channel 1 in its list (if IDs are synchronized by index or hash). It then decrypts using key `e1ad578d...` and obtains the plaintext. It then delivers a `PUSH_RECV_TEXT` (push notification) to its companion app with channel index or name and the message content.

Because channel names and keys have to match on both ends, **all communicating nodes must either be running the new scheme or have been manually configured accordingly**. In practice, mixing firmware versions is fine as long as the channel data (name & key) ends up the same on all.

*   If a new firmware node sends `CMD_SET_CHANNEL("#alert")` without key, an old firmware nodes companion app wouldnt magically know about it unless a user manually adds it there too. Theres no automatic sync of channel membership between nodes in the protocol (aside from the Public default everyone has).

**Special Cases:** The *Public* channel is actually just a normal channel with a known name (often Public without `#`) and a known key distributed with the firmware (not derived from name). It floods by default. One might ask: could Public have been implemented as `#public` using the hash scheme? Possibly, but it wasnt  instead it uses a fixed PSK. That suggests the hash approach was introduced later to allow multiple open channels beyond just one. The **Admin** channel (if used for admin commands) is always encrypted and uses a unique key (not guessable, often user-specific), so it is never a hashtag channel.

In summary, at the protocol level:

*   **Frame format and commands** are unchanged by the hashtag concept  its purely an input handling difference.
*   **Encryption keys** are 32 bytes either way; the `#` just means many devices share knowledge of that key.
*   **Messages** on these channels propagate via MeshCores normal routing (flood unless optimized).
*   **No additional headers or special opcodes** were added for hashtag channels, which made it easy to introduce this feature without breaking compatibility.

## 4. Real-World Usage Patterns of Hashtag Channels

Hashtag channels serve as **public chat rooms or bulletin boards** on the mesh. They are widely used for community coordination, regional communications, and specific topics. Based on community documentation and usage:

*   **Common Hashtag Channels:** Some channel names have become standard in MeshCore communities:
    *   **#public / #general:** While the default channel is usually just named Public, some communities also use `#public` or similar as an open chat. (Note: Public vs #public could be confusing  the former is the default encrypted with a known key; the latter would be a user-made open channel. Typically people stick to the built-in Public or create location-specific ones.)
    *   **#emergency:** A crucial channel intended for emergency communication. Many users pre-configure `#emergency` on their devices so that during a disaster or urgent situation, anyone can broadcast an SOS or information on this channel and all will hear. Because its open, even new responders can join simply by knowing the name. This channel is usually kept clear except for actual emergency traffic. [\[pugetmesh.org\]](https://pugetmesh.org/meshcore/)
    *   **#weather:** Sometimes used by weather stations or enthusiasts to broadcast weather updates to anyone interested in the area. For example, a sensor node might periodically post weather data on `#weather`, allowing any node listening to log or display it.
    *   **#local:** A generic local chat channel. Some communities encourage using a `#local` or `#cityname` channel for neighborhood chatter, so that not all misc messages flood the entire Public network. For instance, in a city-wide mesh, you might have `#downtown`, `#northside` etc., each used by people in those areas.
    *   **#news:** Could be used to broadcast news or announcements. A room server could feed curated news messages into `#news` for others.
    *   **#bot:** Often used for interactions with automated agents or gateways. For example, *MeshBot* (an AI agent for MeshCore) listens on a channel named #bot for user queries. People can send a message on #bot and the MeshBot (running on a node or server) will respond on that channel. Variants like `#bot-tacoma` or `#bot-van` (Vancouver) are used to localize bot coverage. [\[github.com\]](https://github.com/ipnet-mesh/meshbot)
    *   **#test or #testing:** As seen on community sites (like Swiss `#test` and Puget Sound `#testing`), these are channels for experimental and test messages. Users switch to these to avoid cluttering main channels while trying out features or diagnostics. [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/)
    *   **#<region> or #<city>:** Many regions have their own open channels. E.g., `#switzerland` (for nationwide chat in Switzerland), `#bern` (city-specific), `#muenchen` (Munich), `#freiburg` (German region), `#seattle`, `#capitolhill` (a neighborhood in Seattle), etc. Locals join these to talk without bothering those far away. [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/) [\[pugetmesh.org\]](https://pugetmesh.org/meshcore/)
    *   **#qrv:** A specialized channel listed in Swiss and other communities. QRV is a Q-code from amateur radio meaning I am ready  here its used as a channel for amateur radio operators to coordinate mesh usage or bridge ham communications (likely open to all hams in the area). [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/)
    *   **#netzstatus:** German for network status  used in some locations to discuss the mesh networks status or issues. [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/)
    *   **#sports, #chat, #anything:** People are free to invent channels. Puget Mesh listed `#sports` as an example (perhaps to live-chat during local games). Essentially, any topical or community interest can spawn a hashtag channel spontaneously. [\[pugetmesh.org\]](https://pugetmesh.org/meshcore/)

*   **Who Creates Them:** In practice, **no single authority creates a hashtag channel**  the first person to start using it creates it by adding it to their node. When others add the same name, they join that conversation. Often a community organizer or MeshCore enthusiast will propose a channel and publicize it. For example, a disaster preparedness group might say: In emergencies, use channel **#SOS**. The moment at least one node transmits on #SOS and others listen, that channel exists in the mesh. Communities (like MeshCore Switzerland) maintain lists of official or recommended channels and their secrets on wikis and forums. Those effectively coordinate creation. [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/)

*   **Usage Patterns Compared to Private/Direct Messages:**
    *   *Hashtag channels vs Private channels:* Hashtag channels are used when wide, **unrestricted sharing** is desired. Anyone can join without prior arrangement. In contrast, private channels (non-`#`) are for closed groups  e.g. a search-and-rescue team might have a private channel with a secret they share only among themselves for operational comms, while simultaneously monitoring `#emergency` for public distress calls. Private channels require exchanging the key out-of-band (QR code, etc.), so theyre used when confidentiality or limiting participants is important.
    *   *Hashtag channels vs Direct 1-to-1:* Direct messages in MeshCore are typically secure and addressed to a specific node (often using each nodes public key for encryption in newer versions). Those have delivery acknowledgments and do not flood the network. Meanwhile, `#` channels are one-to-many broadcasts  they do not confirm receipt (no ACKs from each listener). They are connectionless; a message goes out and may or may not be heard by others, with no per-recipient retries. This is acceptable for general info and reduces overhead. [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/)
    *   *Traffic and Etiquette:* Because these channels are shared and can reach many, users often adopt radio discipline: e.g., keeping messages short, using agreed language for emergencies, moving detailed chatter off the main emergency channel to some other channel if possible (to keep it clear).
    *   *Bot and Integration Usage:* Some open channels interface with external systems. For example, a weather station might automatically post to `#weather` every hour. A gateway might bridge `#news` to an internet feed. These scenarios leverage the fact that anyone can listen without credentials. However, it also means **malicious or spam devices could inject messages** on these channels since no authentication is required beyond knowing the name. Communities therefore keep an eye on traffic and may switch channels (or resort to a private channel) if interference occurs.

*   **Scale and Range:** Since hashtag channels still use the underlying LoRa network, they are subject to the same range and bandwidth constraints. Using many active open channels in one area means more RF traffic, which can increase collisions. Some communities coordinate to use different **frequencies or presets** for different channels if possible (MeshCore allows channels to have distinct frequency/SF settings but generally the primary and all group channels share the same radio settings so that one node can monitor all with one radio). Typically, all channels on a given device operate on the same frequency but are distinguished by encryption keys; however, MeshCore does support multiple channel definitions with different frequencies/modem parameters too. For instance, a long-range slow channel vs a short-range fast channel. But most hashtag channels use the standard primary network parameters so that any node on the mesh can participate without retuning. [\[localmesh.nl\]](https://www.localmesh.nl/en/meshcore-channel-configuration/), [\[localmesh.nl\]](https://www.localmesh.nl/en/meshcore-channel-configuration/) [\[localmesh.nl\]](https://www.localmesh.nl/en/meshcore-channel-configuration/)

*   **Interactions with Infrastructure Nodes:** Repeaters and room servers can interact with hashtag channels:
    *   A **Repeater** will forward hashtag channel packets just as it does others. Repeaters dont need to decrypt to repeat (they forward everything), so even if a repeater hasnt explicitly joined `#channel`, it will still flood those packets if its operating in flood mode. (Repeaters usually repeat all group traffic by design, but MeshCore repeaters also store routes for directed traffic  for group, flood is used). [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/ripplebiz/MeshCore/1.2-key-concepts-and-terminology), [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/ripplebiz/MeshCore/1.2-key-concepts-and-terminology)
    *   A **Room Server** node can buffer messages for channels. For example, a stationary room server might archive all messages on `#local` for later retrieval. If you go out of range and come back, you could query the room server for messages you missed. This is particularly useful for open channels because anyone can fetch the backlog without needing a key exchange (they just ask the room server while connected on the same channel or via a direct interface). However, room servers likely focus on storing direct messages and maybe a configured subset of channels. One could configure a room server to specifically archive one hashtag channel as a forum.
    *   **Gateway bridges:** Its conceivable to bridge a hashtag channel to the internet or other networks due to its open nature. E.g., a gateway could listen on `#APRS` and forward messages to an APRS-IS feed in ham radio context, etc.

*   **Encryption vs Utility trade-off:** Real-world users recognize that hashtag channels trade confidentiality for ease of use. **They treat these channels as public forums.** As one Swiss MeshCore site states plainly: *Channels starting with `#` are not encrypted, everybody can read along.*. Therefore, they are used for traffic that is intended to be public or at least not sensitive. People will avoid sharing personal or sensitive data on those channels (or if they do, they accept the risk). [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/)

*   **Managing Chaos:** If too many people use one open channel, it can get noisy. Communities might designate multiple channels for different purposes to distribute load (like how large events use multiple frequencies). E.g., `#emergency` only for emergencies, `#chitchat` for general talk, etc., to avoid important messages being lost in a flood of unrelated chatter. There is no hard enforcement of this  its agreed by users.

In practice, the introduction of hashtag channels was a game-changer for MeshCores adoption: it lowered the barrier to entry (no need to share keys to start communicating) and allowed spontaneous networking. Youll often find that if two MeshCore users meet, they can instantly communicate by agreeing on an open channel name, **without fumbling with key exchange**  much like exchanging a radio frequency to talk on. This ease is balanced by understanding that its not secure from eavesdropping.

## 5. Security and Access Control Considerations

By design, **hashtag channels sacrifice cryptographic privacy for ease of access.** They are essentially *party line* channels. Heres a breakdown of their security model:

*   **Encryption:** Technically, hashtag channel traffic *is* encrypted (with AES-256-CTR) like all MeshCore channels. However, the **encryption key is public knowledge** (derived from the channel name, which is not secret). As a result, any adversary who knows or guesses the channel name can also compute the key and decrypt the messages. In other words, **they are encrypted but not secure**. The encryption prevents casual outsiders (who have no idea about MeshCore) from reading the RF signals, but it does nothing against an informed attacker. MeshCores own documentation emphasizes that messages on `#` channels should be considered **publicly readable**. The encryption here functions mainly to integrate with the mesh routing (which expects encrypted packets) rather than to provide security. [\[localmesh.nl\]](https://www.localmesh.nl/en/meshcore-encryption-details/) [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/)

*   **No Authentication:** There is no access control on who can transmit or receive on an open channel. Possession of the name implies full rights. There are **no per-channel passwords or whitelist**  the PSK derived from the name is the only gate, and its a very low bar. This means:
    *   Anyone can join and listen (which is great for inclusivity).
    *   Anyone can also inject messages (which opens the possibility of spam or malicious false messages).
    *   There is no built-in way to verify the identity of a sender on a hashtag channel  messages are not signed by the users identity by default (MeshCore does have an optional signed message type, but thats not about channel permissions, just authenticity of content). So, one must treat communications on open channels with some caution; its as if on a public radio channel where you might get imposters.

*   **Key Distribution:** Because the keys are deterministic, **distribution is trivial**: publish the channel name, and by doing so you have effectively published the key (since the algorithm is known). Communities will often explicitly publish the 32-char hex keys alongside the names  not because its needed to use the channel, but to help users of older software or to double-confirm the hash. For example, the Swiss list shows `#test`  Secret Key: `9cd8fcf22a47333b591d96a2b848b73f`. A user could either type #test into an updated app or manually enter that long key into a device that doesnt do auto-hash; both result in the same ability to join. There is **no need for a secure channel to share keys**  posting on a website or saying over voice use channel #X is enough. [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/), [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/) [\[meshcore.ch\]](https://www.meshcore.ch/channels/)

*   **Same PSK as Public?** No, each hashtag channel has its own unique key (derived from its own name). They do **not all use the same PSK**. This is important to avoid crosstalk: different open channels remain logically separate because their keys differ. The default Public channel uses a well-known PSK (the one baked into devices) which is actually independent of this scheme  historically it was just a constant key on every device. So, `#public` (if someone created it) would have a *different* key than the built-in Public channel. In general, the scheme ensures **distinct channel names  distinct encryption keys**. This also means someone eavesdropping would have to guess the exact name to decode a given packet. If two channels had very similar names, an eavesdropper would still need to try each possible names hash to see which yields intelligible data (though thats not hard if the names are known words). [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/meshcore-dev/MeshCore/8.4-contact-and-channel-storage)

*   **Plaintext vs Derived Key:** One might wonder, why not simply have an unencrypted mode? The choice to use a derived key instead presumably keeps the packet format consistent (always encrypted) and leverages existing crypto without needing a special no encryption case. It also means that while content is open, its not trivially readable by non-MeshCore equipment (someone with an SDR would have to know the protocol and key derivation to decode, which is a minor barrier). But in terms of *MeshCore network security*, a hashtag channel is effectively **no more secure than plain text** because the key is publicly computable.

*   **Privacy and Confidentiality:** Users should never send sensitive personal information (passwords, private plans, etc.) over `#` channels unless they dont mind it being public. For sensitive comms, a private channel or direct message should be used. The MeshCore FAQ and guides strongly encourage using real private channels or direct messaging for anything confidential. The motto is: *If its `#`, treat it like shouting in a public square.* On the flip side, because `#` channels connect strangers, users might want to take care not to reveal private details about themselves on those channels (operational security). [\[jkingsman.github.io\]](https://jkingsman.github.io/meshcore-packet-knife/)

*   **Integrity:** Are messages tamper-evident? MeshCore uses encryption with a counter (CTR mode) which doesnt inherently provide a MAC. However, likely MeshCore includes a message authentication code or at least a CRC for packet integrity. There is no mention of signed messages on group channels by default, so an attacker with the key could alter messages or inject false ones and others couldnt easily tell (aside from content vetting). In personal or team channels, one might trust that only intended members have the key, but in `#` channels, everyone has the key, so you cannot trust the integrity or origin of messages. Some advanced users might use the `TXT_TYPE_SIGNED_PLAIN` (2) message type where each message is digitally signed by the senders private key. If employed, recipients could verify the signature against the senders known public identity, giving some authenticity even on a hashtag channel. However, this is optional and outside the default behavior. It would require each user to share their public key as a contact beforehand. Its more common in direct contacts, not broad channels. [\[deepwiki.com\]](https://deepwiki.com/ripplebiz/MeshCore/6.1-companion-radio-protocol)

*   **Combining with Device Security:** MeshCore devices also have a device-level key for admin control (ensuring random people cant reconfigure your node even on an open channel). The admin functions (over admin channel or direct commands) are always separately secured and not done on these open channels. So an attacker on a hashtag channel cannot, for example, magically reprogram your node; they can only inject normal user messages. [\[localmesh.nl\]](https://www.localmesh.nl/en/meshcore-encryption-details/)

*   **Denial of Service Risks:** Since anyone can transmit, a malicious actor could flood a hashtag channel with garbage, jamming it for others. This is analogous to someone monopolizing a CB radio channel. MeshCore doesnt have a built-in mitigation for that beyond users possibly switching channels or physically locating the spammer. It relies on cooperative use. Because LoRa is long-range, a single bad actor could disrupt a large areas open channel. In critical scenarios, this is a risk; hence for crucial communications, rescue teams might move to a private channel if an open one is under attack. But in practice such jamming has not been prevalent in communities; its a known vulnerability though.

*   **Encryption Key Management:** On the technical side, since the keys are static for each channel name, if one wanted to rotate a hashtag channel key, one would effectively have to change the channel name (e.g., move from `#emergency` to `#emergency2` which obviously is not ideal). There is no concept of rotating keys on open channels  it would defeat the purpose. So those keys remain constant indefinitely (which is fine given theyre public anyway).

*   **The Balance  Discoverability vs Security:** The entire rationale for hashtag channels is to maximize discoverability and ease of community formation. They *intentionally* forego the security of private channels. MeshCore thoughtfully provides both options:
    *   Use a `#` channel when you want *anyone* nearby to be able to join in simply by knowing its name (e.g., calling for help, community chat).
    *   Use a named private channel (or direct messages) for *controlled membership* where you distribute the PSK privately.

The rule of thumb is: **treat hashtag channels as open radio frequencies**. They provide communications without prior arrangement, analogous to emergency channels in two-way radio. Accordingly, MeshCore documentation often **warns users**: if you need confidentiality, do not rely on a `#` channel. Instead, leverage MeshCores strong AES-256 with your own secret keys for those cases. The systems AES-256 implementation is solid  the only weakness of `#` channels is the key selection process (predictable key = no secrecy). [\[jkingsman.github.io\]](https://jkingsman.github.io/meshcore-packet-knife/) [\[localmesh.nl\]](https://www.localmesh.nl/en/meshcore-encryption-details/)

**Access Control:** There is **no built-in access control list** on hashtag channels. You cannot, for example, restrict `#cityhall` to only officials. If privacy or exclusivity is needed, that should be a private channel (with an actual secret key distributed privately). All hashtag channels are effectively **all-read, all-write.** MeshCore doesnt support a hybrid like read-only broadcast channel by design  although one could enforce that via human agreement (e.g., instructing regular users to only listen on `#news` while an authorized station is supposed to be the only one transmitting there). Since nothing technical stops others from transmitting, real enforcement would rely on social or physical measures.

**In summary**, from a security perspective hashtag = **untrusted channel**. They excel at reach and convenience, not at confidentiality or authenticity. MeshCore wisely complements them with secure channel options for when those are needed.

## 6. SDK Integration Guidelines for Hashtag Channels

Integrating hashtag channel support into an SDK (such as a MeshCore .NET SDK) requires handling a few nuances so that developers can use `#` channels as seamlessly as in the official apps. Key considerations and recommendations:

**a. Channel Creation and Key Management:**\
The SDK should abstract the key derivation so that developers (and end-users) only need to specify the channel name:

*   When an SDK user calls something like `AddChannel("#example")` or tries to send a message to #example that isnt configured yet, the SDK should **automatically handle key generation** and channel setup.
*   On a modern firmware (>=1.11.0), you can simply pass the name to the device and let it generate the key. On older firmware, the SDK should detect that scenario and **compute the key client-side**, then call `CMD_SET_CHANNEL` with the Base64 key. To do this detection, the SDK can check the firmware version (via device info) or attempt a `CMD_SET_CHANNEL` without key and see if it fails. However, simplest is to unilaterally compute the key for `#` channels on the SDK side to ensure compatibility. The output (16-byte or 32-byte key) must match the devices algorithm. Based on community info, using *SHA-256 and taking the first 16 bytes* is the known method. [\[pugetmesh.org\]](https://pugetmesh.org/meshcore/), [\[pugetmesh.org\]](https://pugetmesh.org/meshcore/)
    *   **Backward compatibility approach:** If the SDK targets mixed environments, it can always send the key. New firmware will simply accept the provided key (even if it could have generated the same itself). This does no harm. So computing the hash in the SDK and sending it is a safe universal approach. Alternatively, the SDK could have a toggle or auto-detect: firmware 1.11 supports an auto flag  but since the protocol doesnt explicitly have one, its moot. In short: **to maximize compatibility, the SDK should itself implement the name-to-key hash** for `#` channels.
*   Ensure the name string is properly formatted (no trailing spaces, include the `#` literally as the first char). The device will store exactly whats sent. So the SDK might want to sanitize or validate input: e.g., restrict to `a-z,0-9,-` after the `#` (the MeshCore Packet Knife tool indicates allowed characters for room names are alphanumeric and dash, with some rules about dashes). Enforcing the same rules prevents accidental keys mismatch (likely the firmware and official app enforce or expect similar rules). [\[jkingsman.github.io\]](https://jkingsman.github.io/meshcore-packet-knife/)
*   If a user tries to add a channel **without** a `#` and provides no key, thats an error  the SDK should prompt for a key in that case, because only `#` triggers auto-key logic. Conversely, if they include `#`, assume they want an open channel.

**b. SendChannelMessageAsync Implementation:**\
When a developer uses a high-level method like `SendChannelMessageAsync(string channelName, string message)`:

*   **Name resolution:** The SDK should map the `channelName` to a channel index on the device. If the channel is already known (perhaps stored in an internal dictionary from a previous discovery or add), use that index. If not:
    *   If the name starts with `#`, the SDK can **automatically create the channel on the device** before sending. This could involve invoking `CMD_SET_CHANNEL` with the name (and hashed key if needed). This makes the method fire and forget: user just calls send, and the SDK ensures the channel exists then sends the message. This is convenient but has a side effect of silently adding channels. That is probably acceptable given the expectation that `#` channels are easy to use. (It would mimic an app where typing a message to a new `#` channel implicitly joins it.)
    *   Alternatively, the SDK could throw an exception like Unknown channel if not found. However, for `#` channels, auto-creation is more user-friendly. Since `#` has no entry barrier, the SDK might as well add it. For non-`#` names, auto-creation is not appropriate without a key, so in those cases the SDK should error or require additional parameters (like a key).
*   **Prefix handling:** The SDK should *not* remove the `#` in calls  the `#` is part of the actual channel identifier. It might be tempting to treat it as a marker and strip it, but the firmware expects the name with `#`. For instance, sending bot vs #bot are totally different channels (one secured by who-knows-what key, one open). So keep the `#`. The only place to omit it is if you were computing a hash: you must include `#` in the hash input as well, otherwise youd derive a wrong key.
*   **Caching index:** After a channel is created, store its index internally so subsequent sends or queries dont repeat the creation. The device will also remember it persistently in `/channels2`.

**c. DiscoverDeviceChannels / MapChannelNameToIndex:**\
If the SDK has a method to fetch the list of channels from the device (e.g., `DiscoverDeviceChannelsAsync()` that internally calls `CMD_GET_CHANNEL` repeatedly), it will retrieve names including any `#`. The SDK should present those to the user as-is (with `#`). It may be helpful to visually distinguish open channels in an API (maybe a property IsPublic = true if name starts with `#`), but that can also be left to developer interpretation. The main thing is to ensure no confusion such as trimming the `#` prefix.

For `MapChannelNameToIndex(string name)`, the SDK might:

*   Look through the cached channel list for a matching name. If found, return index.
*   If not found and the name starts `#`, it could optionally create it (similar to the send logic). But a safer pattern is to provide a separate explicit call to add channel, and have Map just do lookup. That way, usage is clear: call `EnsureChannelExists("#name")` which under the hood adds if needed, then MapChannelNameToIndex will work.
*   In any case, MapChannelNameToIndex for `#` channels should be O(1) if you maintain a `Dictionary<string,int>` of channels. Populating that dictionary initially via `CMD_GET_CHANNEL` responses is wise. Keep it updated if channels are added/removed during the session.

**d. Error Handling & Fallbacks:**

*   If the device is older and the SDK did not send a key for a `#` channel, the `CMD_SET_CHANNEL` might respond with an error (perhaps invalid parameter or similar if it insisted on a PSK). The SDK should catch such errors. A robust approach as noted is to always provide the key, avoiding the error entirely.
*   If a user tries to send on `#foo` but the devices channel table is full (40 channels already), the `CMD_SET_CHANNEL` would fail. The SDK should surface a clear error (e.g., Channel table full, cannot join #foo). Ideally, also instruct the user to remove some channel first. This is a rare scenario but possible if a user subbed to many channels.
*   If sending fails because the channel doesnt exist and auto-creation was off, the SDK error should mention that they need to add the channel or allow auto-add.
*   The SDK should allow sending even if no one is currently out there  the mesh will just broadcast; the message might not be received by anyone if no ones listening, but thats fine. Theres usually no delivery acknowledgment on group sends, so the SDK typically just returns after issuing the send command (maybe indicating success sending to radio, but it cant guarantee a recipient got it).

**e. Representing Hashtag Channels in the API:**\
To integrate well:

*   Provide an intuitive way to create or join them. e.g. `JoinChannel("#channelName")` in the SDK that behind the scenes calls `CMD_SET_CHANNEL`. This function should ideally not require providing a key for `#` names; it can figure it out. For non-`#` it might require a key argument.
*   Provide utility to list channels (the ones configured on device). The SDK might mark which are `#` in output (like prefix in name already does that).
*   If the SDK offers events for incoming messages, it should include the channel info. E.g., an `OnMessageReceived` event could provide a channel name. The SDK will likely have to map the channel index in the incoming push notification from the device back to the channel name. That means the SDK must know indexname mapping (again via caching results of GET\_CHANNEL). The push likely gives channel index or a short ID, the SDK then says Message on #emergency: ....
*   Cross-platform: The .NET SDKs behavior should mirror what the official Android/iOS apps do. Those apps, in newer versions, allow the user to type `#something` as a destination and automatically handle it. The SDK should do the same.

**f. Efficiency (Caching Strategy):**\
Since hashing channel names to keys is quick (SHA-256) and channel lists are small, performance isnt a big issue. That said:

*   Cache known channel indices and names on connect to avoid repeatedly querying the device for the same info.
*   If the SDK adds a channel, update the cache immediately instead of waiting for a new GET refresh.
*   If the SDK removes a channel (some APIs let you remove channels by index/name), update cache accordingly.
*   The SDK could pre-compute the hash key for a `#` channel and store it if needed to compare or reuse, but its probably not necessary to expose that to users. Typically, you wont need the key on the outside (its internal). Only case might be if the SDK allows exporting a channel for someone else, e.g., output a QR code that encodes name+key.

**g. Cross-Platform Behavior Differences:**\
MeshCores hashtag channels themselves behave the same on all device platforms (ESP32-based T-LoRa boards, etc.). The differences might come from UI or OS limitations:

*   For example, some low-end devices (like certain Arduino-based nodes) might not easily allow typing a `#` in their interface. Thats why communities publish the hex keys  so those users can copy-paste the key rather than type the name. A PC or phone SDK doesnt have that limitation. But be aware some older official app versions may not have recognized `#` as special; ensure your SDK does.
*   Another subtlety: the devices storage file `/channels2` is finite  an SDK on a PC might try to add dozens of channels because its easy via automation, but the device will cap at 40. So the SDK should either know the limit via device info or handle errors gracefully as mentioned.
*   Different MeshCore firmware might have slight differences in allowed name characters (e.g., older versions might have allowed spaces or uppercase, but current convention is typically lowercase and digits). Its best to follow the latest convention for compatibility. The SDK could enforce name to lowercase and a certain charset to avoid creating channels that others might not join due to case mismatch, etc. For instance, if someone added #Weather with capital W on one device and another added #weather, those count as different names (and thus different keys). This could fragment communications unintentionally. The SDK can mitigate this by normalizing (e.g., always sending lowercase for hashtag names, since communities always publish them in lowercase).
*   The SDK documentation should highlight that `#` channels are not secure, guiding developers to not pass sensitive info there and to use private channels for that.

**h. Logging and Debugging:**\
Its useful for the SDK to log when it auto-creates a hashtag channel or when it computes a key, since this is implicit behavior. For instance, a debug log: Channel #example not found, creating with derived key. And maybe log the derived key in hex if in debug mode (though thats technically not sensitive, one might still avoid printing keys to logs to not confuse users).

**i. Use Cases the SDK Should Make Easy:**

*   **Broadcast on an open channel:** e.g., a developer wants to broadcast a sensor reading to anyone listening on #weather. They should be able to do:
    ```csharp
    client.SendChannelMessageAsync("#weather", $"Temp={t}");
    ```
    and the SDK ensures #weather exists (adds if needed) and sends it. Next time, it reuses the channel.
*   **Listen on an open channel:** e.g., a developer wants to handle incoming emergency messages:
    ```csharp
    client.JoinChannel("#emergency");
    client.OnMessageReceived += (ch, msg) => {
        if(ch == "#emergency"){ ... }
    };
    ```
    Under the hood, `JoinChannel` ensures subscription. The event passes `#emergency` as channel. The developer doesnt worry about keys or indices.
*   **List channels for UI:**
    ```csharp
    var channels = await client.GetChannelsAsync();
    ```
    It returns something like `["Public", "#emergency", "#weather", "PrivateTeam"]`. The developer can display those. Theyll see which ones have `#` and infer the open ones.

**j. Edge  Removing Hashtag Channel via SDK:**
If the SDK exposes a remove function, simply call `CMD_SET_CHANNEL` with that index and an empty name or use a `CMD_REMOVE_CHANNEL` if it exists (not listed in protocol snippet, but perhaps the way is to set name =  or there might be a different code; looking at protocol, theres `CMD_SET_CHANNEL` to update and maybe setting name empty could clear it  but likely a dedicated command might exist or one sets the name to 0 length to delete). Regardless, this isn't special for `#` channels; it works the same as others. The SDK just needs to manage its cache.

In summary, the SDK should make the use of hashtag channels **transparent and convenient**:

*   Accept `#` names wherever a channel identifier is needed, handle the hashing internally.
*   Ensure compatibility with older firmware by providing keys when necessary.
*   Avoid requiring the user/developer to manually deal with the PSK for open channels  thats the whole point of this feature.

## 7. Evolution and Compatibility Across Firmware Versions

**Evolution of Hashtag Channel Support:** MeshCores hashtag channel feature appears to have been introduced around firmware v1.11.0 (circa 2024) as an extension of the channel system. Earlier MeshCore versions did not inherently know how to derive keys from names  they relied solely on configured PSKs. Some key points in its evolution:

*   **Pre-1.11 (Older Firmware):** All channels had to be configured with an explicit key. The concept of a public channel existed (the default channel with known key AQ== or similar), but there was no dynamic derivation of new channel keys from names. If a user wanted a new open channel, they would have to pick a key and share it. In practice, before hashtag channels, many communities might have simply reused the default Public channel for all open comms, or manually set up additional channels by sharing keys as text or QR codes. For example, a group might say: Use channel `Emergency` with key `0xABCD...`  effectively functioning like a hashtag channel but without the convenience (everyone still had to get that key string). [\[localmesh.nl\]](https://www.localmesh.nl/en/meshcore-encryption-details/)
    *   The idea of using the channel name as the seed for a key likely evolved from seeing that pattern and wanting to streamline it.

*   **Firmware v1.11.0 Introduction:** In firmware 1.11, the MeshCore devs implemented the auto-key feature for `#` prefix. This allowed an unlimited number of distinct open channels without coordinating new random keys. Its a backward-compatible change in the sense that it doesnt break anything for older nodes; its additive:
    *   New firmware will automatically hash the key if it sees `#`.
    *   It likely also sets a flag in channel metadata (maybe in ChannelDetails or somewhere) to denote that the key was generated (for its own knowledge, or maybe it simply relies on the presence of `#` in name at runtime whenever needed).
    *   There might have been minor changes in the companion app protocols to not require a PSK for those channels. Possibly `CMD_SET_CHANNEL` was always capable of being called with just a name and treat missing PSK as error previously. They may have modified it such that if name starts with `#` and PSK field length is zero, instead of error, it computes key. This is speculation, but logically how to avoid introducing a new command.

*   **Support in Companion Apps:** Alongside firmware changes, the official MeshCore companion apps (Android, iOS, etc.) were updated to utilize this feature. E.g., after v1.11, the app UI might automatically prepend `#` for known open channels or allow the user to just type it and not ask for a key. Before, creating a channel always required entering a key (or scanning QR). Now, if you type a name with `#`, the key field might auto-fill or disappear. This update timing suggests that by late 2024 or early 2025, the ecosystem widely acknowledged hashtag channels.

*   **Backward Compatibility Behavior:** In a mixed network:
    *   An **old device (pre-1.11)** doesnt know about the `#` convention internally. However, it can still participate in a hashtag channel if someone configures it with the correct key. This is why community lists include the hex keys  so that if you have an older firmware or a device interface that doesnt auto-derive, you can manually join by entering both name and key.
    *   New and old devices can talk fine as long as they have matching names and keys. The new device might have gotten the key via hash, the old via manual entry, but once set, theyre on equal footing.
    *   **One-Way Transparency:** New firmware will happily talk on, say, `#test` and assume whoever hears it will have the key. An old firmware that didnt configure `#test` (because the user didnt know to) will just ignore those packets (they wont decrypt properly against any of its known keys, so theyll be dropped as noise). It wont know hey this is a hashtag channel I could join if I knew name  it has no such logic.
    *   Hence, the onus is on the human/companion software to ensure older nodes are manually configured to match. This typically means if older nodes are in your network, you have to distribute not just the name but the key (or ensure they run an updated companion that does it for them).
    *   The **companion app version matters**: A new phone app connecting to an old firmware device can actually bridge the gap: because the app can implement the hashing. For example, if the Android app is new but the device firmware is old, the app can still allow adding #channel and simply send the computed key via `CMD_SET_CHANNEL`. The device doesnt know it was a hashtag channel in concept; it just stores the key and name. It works. The user experience is seamless because the companion app took over the feature. This is likely what happened in practice: the companion apps incorporate this logic to maintain compatibility with older node firmware. They know the firmware version from `DEVICE_INFO` and decide whether to auto-send key or let firmware handle it. But they probably always send it to be safe.
    *   Conversely, an old companion app (from before hashtag support) talking to a new firmware might actually *prevent* using the feature. E.g., if the old app insists on a key for any new channel and the user doesnt have one for `#topic`, they cant create it. Or if the old app doesnt allow `#` as first char (some early UIs might have limited allowed characters), then the user cant even type it. In those cases, the user would need to update the app or manually compute a key and input both. This underscores that to fully benefit, both firmware and app should be up-to-date. However, since the question context is an SDK, we assume the SDK is being developed with awareness of `#` channels, so it will effectively act as a new companion app approach even if connecting to older firmware.

*   **Known Limitations in Older Versions:** Before this feature, a lot of people used the single Public channel for everything, meaning **everyone shared one key**. That key was widely known (TooManySecrets in Meshtastic, or a base64 string in MeshCores case) which meant if you were within range you could hear everything on public. The problem was lack of topic segregation and potential excessive flooding. The introduction of unlimited hashtag channels solved that by letting people carve the network into topics without having to share new secrets each time. One limitation though: older devices that aren't updated might remain stuck just on Public and oblivious to others, causing a possible communication gap. Communities handled this by pushing firmware updates or by educating users to manually add the new channels with keys. Over time, as most devices get updated, this becomes less of an issue.

*   **Possible Future Evolution:** The question doesnt ask for speculation beyond current state, but its worth noting: The scheme might evolve to different hashing or adding subtle improvements (for example, maybe using full 32 bytes of SHA-256 instead of 16 bytes  currently evidence shows 16 bytes are used because they publish a 128-bit key for `#` channels, but maybe internally they actually use all 32 bytes? If each channel record stores 32 bytes secret, they could use entire SHA-256 output as the key. We saw in Puget list keys are 128-bit though, suggesting they might actually only be using 128-bit keys for open channels while still reserving 256-bit for private? Or they truncated for publishing simplicity. Its a bit unclear. Possibly they do use the full 256-bit (32 bytes) from the name by taking SHA-256(name) = 32 bytes and using that entirely as the AES-256 key. If so, the published Secret Key strings we see might be truncated just for display. Actually, re-check: The Swiss site calls those 32-hex-digit strings Secret Key. Thats 16 bytes. If only half the hash is used for actual key, those hex strings *are* the actual key being used. If they used full 32 bytes, the hex would be 64 digits. They gave 32-digit, implying the actual PSK length is 16 bytes for those channels. Maybe they decided 128-bit is enough for open channels (since theyre not trying to be super secure anyway)? But that would reduce encryption strength on those channels to 128-bit from the standard 256-bit. Possibly an oversight or a simplification for opens? Alternatively, they might be showing just the first 16 bytes for brevity, expecting thats enough to join because older devices maybe only supported 16-byte PSKs originally (Meshtastic originally used 4-word (128-bit) PSKs and later extended to 256-bit? Theres some cross-history with Meshtastic, which used 13-byte channel names hashed into 16-byte AES keys in older versions. MeshCore might have inherited or diverged from that approach). This is a technical detail: the ChannelDetails shows 32-byte secret fields, so its capable of 256-bit. Its likely MeshCore actually uses full 256-bit keys for all channels including `#`. Perhaps communities only print 128-bit just because historically thats how Meshtastic did it and it might be that the second half is a fixed pattern if original Meshtastics scheme was different. Without more info, we provide whats observed. Regardless, from an SDK perspective, follow what the official tools do: presumably compute SHA-256 and use the full 32 bytes as the key when sending to device, because the device expects 32 bytes to store. If it only uses first 16 internally, its the devices business.)

To sum up the compatibility:

*   **New SDK + New Firmware:** Everything works straightforwardly (just name needed).
*   **New SDK + Old Firmware:** The SDK should send keys to ensure functionality. After that, comms with other updated devices is fine as long as keys match.
*   **Old SDK/App + New Firmware:** Might not leverage new features, could cause missing out on open channels or require manual keys.
*   **Mixed Nodes:** Provided all nodes have the same channel config (via either method), they interoperate. No special compatibility mode is needed on-air; a packet from a new node on `#channel` is just an encrypted packet. Old node will decrypt it successfully if it had the key manually configured.

Given the questions focus, the key takeaway for backward compatibility is: **to support older firmware, handle key derivation in the SDK** and understand that older devices treat these channels as regular ones with a user-supplied key. The network can include a mix, but its managed via correct key distribution.

## 8. Interoperability and Standards Context

**MeshCore-Specific Feature:** The hashtag channel concept is specific to MeshCore (and partially inspired by similar ideas in Meshtastic, its predecessor/parallel project). There isnt a broader LoRa mesh standard that defines open channels by name. MeshCore implemented this as a usability improvement. In standard LoRaWAN or other networks, this concept doesnt exist  those typically have fixed keys or dev addresses. So one should not expect devices from other systems (e.g., Meshtastic or LoRaWAN) to understand MeshCore `#` channels. This is a MeshCore-internal convention.

*   MeshCore vs Meshtastic: Meshtastic (an earlier mesh project) had channel names and channel psk. The default was Default channel with a known PSK. Later Meshtastic also allowed a secondary channel with user-defined key. But Meshtastic didnt have the hashtag naming scheme for deriving keys on the fly. MeshCore evolved from that by adding this feature (MeshCores dev is Scott from Meshtastic, and he extended many ideas). So, its not part of an official standard, but its within the open-source community practice.

**Interaction with Room Servers:** A MeshCore Room Server is like a message BBS node that stores and forwards messages when requested. Room servers can host *rooms* which are essentially channels with history. A hashtag channel can effectively act as a room if a room server subscribes to it:

*   A room server node could be configured to join `#channel` and keep messages for a period. Users coming online could query the server for missed messages on that channel. The query and sync logic is more complex (likely using a separate protocol or direct connection), but conceptually it can provide persistence.
*   Because hashtag channels are open, anyone with access to the room server (physically or via a direct connection) could retrieve the stored messages  theres no additional access check besides knowing the channel name. This is convenient for, say, an online portal: you could have a web-connected MeshCore room server logging all `#switzerland` messages and displaying them on a live feed publicly (in fact, communities might do that as a way to monitor the mesh from the internet).
*   **Interoperability:** That scenario shows how `#` channels blur into other communication realms. Its easy to bridge open channels to external systems because you dont have to manage keys securely.

**IoT Sensors on # Channels:** MeshCore can also be used for IoT sensors (telemetry). A sensor might send data on a channel, and multiple displays could show it. If its non-sensitive (weather, environmental), using a hashtag channel is perfect. Anyone with a MeshCore device can pick it up. This is analogous to how ham radio APRS works (beacons on a known frequency for weather, etc.). Indeed, the presence of channel `#qrv` suggests interaction with ham radio community interests  perhaps bridging to ham networks.

**Future/Standards:** The LoRa Alliance doesnt define anything about mesh communication at such a high level; MeshCore is an independent protocol. Its essentially a de-facto standard among its users now that `#` indicates open channel. Its possible that other mesh projects could adopt similar ideas (since its handy). But theres no official cross-compatibility  e.g., a Meshtastic node wont understand the significance of `#` in a MeshCore channel name; those are entirely separate systems despite similarities.

**Interoperability with encryption and networks:** Because hashtag channels use a known derivation, one interesting aspect is that **different MeshCore networks could converge if they choose the same channel name.** For example, if two groups in different areas both use `#emergency`, their networks arent physically connected unless a node moves between them or a long-range link exists. But if one were to travel, their device on `#emergency` would immediately integrate into the new areas emergency channel, since its the same key. Thats interoperability by convention. We see that in practice:

*   Many regions explicitly use `#emergency`. So a rescuer from region A going to region B who has `#emergency` configured will be on the right channel instantly. This is a powerful feature for mutual aid scenarios.
*   It also means if neighboring regions inadvertently use the same open channel name for different purposes, they could interfere at the boundaries. So some coordination or using distinctive names helps. (Using country or city tags in names helps scope them.)

**Community Conventions:**

*   They often use all-lowercase for channel names, and avoid spaces. Dashes are used for multi-word (e.g., `#bot-van` for bot Vancouver).
*   A convention has emerged to prepend `#` for these open channels (the system enforces it for key derivation, so its not optional  open channels *must* start with `#` to be treated as such).
*   Another convention: Because `#` channels are read by anyone, some communities might suffix `-TX` or such if its meant to be one-way. But thats rare; more likely they just socially agree only county officials transmit on #countyalert, others only listen but cannot technically enforce it.
*   Channel lists are often shared on forums (like the Swiss list or Puget list). This is akin to how one would publish frequencies in radio. [\[pugetmesh.org\]](https://pugetmesh.org/meshcore/)

**Security Interoperability:**

*   We should note: *Public key cryptography*: MeshCore in recent versions introduced use of public keys for direct messages and perhaps for contact exchange, but group channels remain symmetric (PSK) oriented. The hashtag channels did not switch to a pubkey model because group PKI is complicated (would require distributed key agreement or one sender broadcasting encrypted separately to each recipients key  not feasible for LoRa flooding). So they stick with symmetric PSK for simplicity.
*   Therefore, the main security difference with a private channel is just whether the PSK is known to outsiders. Theres no concept like only authorized nodes (with certain pubkeys) can join a # channel  that would contradict the whole idea.

**Integration with External Systems:**

*   Because content is effectively public, third-party services or gateways can integrate without worrying about key management. For instance, one could deploy a MeshCore to Internet gateway that listens on certain `#` channels and posts the messages to a web server or Discord, etc. This is in fact being done in some communities, creating an extended reach. Conversely, a gateway can inject messages into the mesh by transmitting on a `#` channel (with appropriate hardware).
*   *Example:* A weather station might also post to an online API; the mesh devices can receive it via `#weather`. Or a remote operator can send an emergency instruction via an internet-connected MeshCore node on `#emergency` to field teams.

In summary, hashtag channels greatly improve **interoperability among MeshCore users** (everyone with the name can talk, no prior link needed) but **do not interoperate with other systems** unless those systems explicitly adopt the same scheme. They function as open standards *within* the MeshCore ecosystem  much like an agreed radio frequency. And indeed, communities treat them as such: documented, shared, and standardized naming (like `#qrv` across regions for ham coordination, etc.).
